    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nNvim C API is not officially supported. (However, our cmake definition has a `libnvim` target, which is used by e.g. VimR)\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\n1. Decide which C types our C interface will use. Do we need to avoid structs?\r\n2. Provide `*.h` headers for consumers include.\r\n3. Declare `SONAME`\r\n4. Document ABI (not API) contract. (+test coverage)\r\n5. Document the correct usage of `libnvim`\r\n\r\n### Open questions\r\n\r\n- extra considerations for UIs that want to embed `libnvim` ? #2034\r\n    - current process for UIs embedding Nvim in-process is: link to `libnvim` and speak msgpack to it (same as out-of-process UI).\r\n- via @dundargoc  :\r\n  >  libnvim. Does it need explicitly need to be a static library? Couldn't we just not set the type?\r\n  > Apparently you're not supposed to specify if a library is meant to be static or shared anyway so outside projects can choose what type of library they want to use.\r\n\r\n### Related\r\n\r\n- https://flameeyes.blog/2012/03/07/why-foreign-function-interfaces-are-not-an-easy-answer/\r\n    - > example: moving from `uint32_t` to `uint64_t` for the parameters of a function: ... such a change in the C ABI would make the change incompatible, as the size of the parameters on the stack doubled.\r\n- https://flameeyes.blog/2010/10/08/linkers-and-names/\r\n    - > neither the link editor nor the loader have a real concept of “ABI version”, which is why they don’t enforce it at all\r\n",
